                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d723">
                <head>No. 719.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Heap</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Blaine</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Constantinople</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1881-06-25">
                            <hi rend="italic">June</hi> 25, 1881</date>. (Received July
                        16.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 22.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I am in receipt of two communications from the
                    minister for foreign affairs, dated the 22d and 23d instant, respectively. In
                    the first his excellency informs me that three of the brigands who robbed the
                    Rev. Mr. Pierce and his companions near Baghchejik have been arrested,
                    identified, and will shortly be tried. His excellency adds that he has written
                    to the prefecture of the city requesting that the proceedings in this case be
                    hastened.</p>
                <p>In his second note his excellency states that the entire band of brigands who
                    robbed Mr. Montgomery, the United States consular agent at Marach, have been
                    apprehended, and that all the articles stolen from Mr. Montgomery have been
                    recovered and restored to him.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>G. H. HEAP.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
